      Tether
   =20
 =20

In principle, Tether, the big stablecoin issuer,=C2=A0has an extremely simp=
le business model:
=09People give it dollars.=09It gives them back Tether stablecoins, or =E2=
=80=9CUSDT.=E2=80=9D Each USDT is meant to be worth $1, and the exchange ra=
te is one USDT for one dollar. If people give Tether $10,000, it gives them=
 back 10,000 USDT.=09Tether keeps the dollars somewhere safe, presumably ea=
rning interest on them, which it uses to pay operating expenses and executi=
ve salaries and so forth.=09If people want their dollars back, they can giv=
e Tether USDT and get back dollars, again one-for-one.

As of its most recent =E2=80=A6=C2=A0auditor-related thingy? =E2=80=A6 Teth=
er had about $67=C2=A0billion worth of assets backing about $66 billion of =
Tether tokens, though that was in December 2022 and it has grown since then=
.
This is, in principle, a very simple and attractive business, but Tether ha=
s found it hilariously difficult as an=C2=A0operational=C2=A0matter. In pri=
