<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Tether</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In principle, Tether, the big stablecoin issue=
r,=C2=A0has an extremely simple business model:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">People give it dollars.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It gives them back Tether stablecoins, or =E2=
=80=9CUSDT.=E2=80=9D Each USDT is meant to be worth $1, and the exchange ra=
te is one USDT for one dollar. If people give Tether $10,000, it gives them=
 back 10,000 USDT.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Tether keeps th=
e dollars somewhere safe, presumably earning interest on them, which it use=
s to pay operating expenses and executive salaries and so forth.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If people want their dollars back, they can =
give Tether USDT and get back dollars, again one-for-one.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As of its most recent =E2=80=A6=C2=A0<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30747147.267413/aHR0cHM6L=
y9hc3NldHMuY3RmYXNzZXRzLm5ldC92eXNlODhjZ3dmYmwvNTNMOFlSTTRaSENFZXFscEtiYzNR=
OC8yZTZjYmNkMTU5M2IzZTVlYTg2NzcxOGM1OTM4ZDZjOC9TdGRfSVNBRV8zMDAwUl9PcGluaW9=
uX0JET18zMS0xMi0yMDIyX1RldGhlcl9DUlIucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc47e3ea4=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">auditor-related thingy</a>? =E2=80=A6 Tether had about $67=C2=A0b=
illion worth of assets backing about $66 billion of Tether tokens, though t=
hat was in December 2022 and it has <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/30747147.267413/aHR0cHM6Ly90ZXRoZXIudG8vZW4vdHJhbnNwYXJlb=
mN5Lw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa0625a15" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">grown since then</a>.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is, in principle, a very simple and attra=
ctive business, but Tether has found it hilariously difficult as an=C2=A0<e=
m>operational=C2=A0</em>matter. In principle the way you do this business i=
s you have people wire you the dollars, and you send them their USDT (on th=
e blockchain), and you keep the dollars in a bank account or money-market f=
und or Treasury bills or whatever earning like 4%, and if people want their=
 dollars back you wire them the dollars, and meanwhile you=E2=80=99re earni=
ng like $200 million a month on the float and life is good.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in practice what seems to happen is that p=
eople go to their banks and are like =E2=80=9CI would like to wire Tether $=
1 million to buy stablecoins=E2=80=9D and the banks say =E2=80=9Cno.=E2=80=
=9D And then Tether goes to banks and says =E2=80=9Cwe would like to deposi=
t the $67=C2=A0billion backing=C2=A0our stablecoins=E2=80=9D and the banks =
say =E2=80=9Cno.=E2=80=9D And then people go to Tether and say =E2=80=9CI w=
ould like you to wire me back $1 million for my stablecoins=E2=80=9D and ev=
eryone=E2=80=99s banks say =E2=80=9Cno.=E2=80=9D I am exaggerating, but the=
 basic fact of Tether=E2=80=99s life seems to be that a lot of the financia=
l intermediaries =E2=80=94=C2=A0banks, brokers, auditors =E2=80=94=C2=A0who=
 would normally be thrilled to work with a $67 billion pot of money, for so=
me reason, aren=E2=80=99t. So Tether has to do this very simple banking bus=
iness in a very complicated way.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How would you do it, if you were them? On Frid=
ay the Wall Street Journal had an article about one possible answer, well s=
ummarized by the headline: =E2=80=9CCrypto Companies Behind Tether <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30747147.267413/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9jcnlwdG8tY29tcGFuaWVzLWJlaGluZC10ZXRoZXItdXNl=
ZC1mYWxzaWZpZWQtZG9jdW1lbnRzLWFuZC1zaGVsbC1jb21wYW5pZXMtdG8tZ2V0LWJhbmstYWN=
jb3VudHMtZjc5OGIwYTU_bW9kPWJyZWFraW5nbmV3cw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB575596=
4f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">Used Falsified Documents and Shell Companies to Get Bank Accou=
nts</a>.=E2=80=9D Well, sure:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tether=E2=80=99s efforts to keep bank access g=
rew urgent in March 2017, when Wells Fargo &amp; Co. stopped processing tra=
nsactions from several Taiwanese accounts that Tether was using. =E2=80=A6<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Phil Potter, Tether=E2=80=99s now-former chief=
 strategy officer, sought to calm anxious users on a conference call a few =
weeks later, saying Tether and Bitfinex had always found a solution. =E2=80=
=9CThere=E2=80=99s been lots of sort of cat-and-mouse tricks that everyone =
in the industry has to avail themselves of,=E2=80=9D Mr. Potter said on a r=
ecording of the call.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The companies opened new accounts by using est=
ablished business executives and tweaking company names, according to the d=
ocuments.=C2=A0In Taiwan, the accounts were held in trust by Chrise Lee, an=
 executive of Hylab Technology Ltd., which makes television set-top boxes. =
But the accounts were opened under the name Hylab Holdings Ltd., documents =
show. Mr. Lee didn=E2=80=99t reply to a request for comment.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Right, one way around the problem is that you =
have all the customers wire money to Legitimate Import/Export Ltd. and labe=
l it =E2=80=9Cfor televisions,=E2=80=9D that is an approach. We <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30747147.267413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMjQvc29tZS1zcGFjcy1o=
YXZlLXNwYXJlLWNhc2g_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMwNjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWF=
pbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzA2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb2=
5leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb45d8bc9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked last month</a=
> about how Sam Bankman-Fried is facing bank-fraud charges for, um,=C2=A0th=
at.=C2=A0Early in FTX Trading Ltd.=E2=80=99s existence it had trouble getti=
ng bank accounts for itself (as a crypto exchange, a high-risk sort of busi=
ness), so it had customers wire money to accounts under different names, an=
d then sort of held the money in trust for the customers and figured it wou=
ld all work out. Then it allegedly stole the money, but that is a separate =
point from the bank fraud; even if the money was still there, this is the s=
ort of thing that can get you in trouble. You never want to use the phrase =
=E2=80=9Ccat-and-mouse tricks=E2=80=9D=C2=A0about your banking relationship=
s!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here's another anecdote=C2=A0about Tether and =
its sister company, the crypto exchange Bitfinex:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tether and Bitfinex executives also tried to e=
xpand their bank access with an account at New York=E2=80=99s Signature Ban=
k, which had made a push into crypto. Signature had closed two accounts tie=
d to the companies earlier that year, according to the documents, and rejec=
ted another attempt by Bitfinex that fall, according to a person familiar w=
ith the matter.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Signature bankers were then introduced to a co=
mpany called AML Global, an aviation fuel broker that was looking to open a=
n account.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The account would be controlled by Christopher=
 Harborne, according to the application, which said it would be used to tra=
de cryptocurrency primarily on a well-known exchange called Kraken for the =
purposes of hedging currency exposure.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am going to stop you right there: You are se=
lling=C2=A0<em>aviation fuel</em>, and you are hedging your=C2=A0<em>curren=
cy exposure=C2=A0</em>by=C2=A0<em>trading crypto? </em>=C2=A0I think the=C2=
=A0<em>best</em>-case scenario there is that you are lying to act as a fron=
t for a crypto exchange! Imagine walking into a bank and saying =E2=80=9Coh=
 yeah I am in a business where I sell aviation fuel for crypto=E2=80=9D! Wh=
at will they think? Who do they think is buying aviation fuel with crypto? =
How is that a=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>story?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway =E2=80=9Cfalsified documents and shell =
companies to get bank accounts=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>one possible =
approach for Tether. (=E2=80=9CTether said the Journal=E2=80=99s report was=
 =E2=80=98wholly inaccurate and misleading=E2=80=99=C2=A0and said that Teth=
er and Bitfinex have =E2=80=98world-class compliance programs=E2=80=99 and =
adhere to legal requirements.=E2=80=9D) There are others. One is to find so=
me money-transmitting partner who is a little more risk-tolerant than, you =
know, Wells Fargo, but that has its own problems:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bitfinex also moved more than $1 billion into =
a Panama-based payment processor called Crypto Capital Corp., despite the l=
ack of a written agreement between the companies, court records show. Crypt=
o Capital is now defunct. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By October 2018, the Crypto Capital plan was b=
ackfiring. Around $850 million of the companies=E2=80=99 funds were seized =
by authorities in the U.S. and Europe as a result of criminal investigation=
s into bank fraud and alleged money laundering. Customers had trouble withd=
rawing funds, tether lost its peg to the U.S. dollar and Bitfinex borrowed =
from Tether to cover the hole in its balance sheet.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The following year, Bitfinex said it was defra=
uded by Crypto Capital and is still fighting the seizures.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The advantage of finding a payment processor t=
hat doesn=E2=80=99t require a lot of paperwork is that they=E2=80=99ll take=
 your money=C2=A0without a lot of paperwork. The disadvantage is that they =
won=E2=80=99t give it back. (We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/30747147.267413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDQtMjYvdGhpbmdzLWdvdC13ZWlyZC1mb3Itc3RhYmxlY29pbi10ZXRo=
ZXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMwNjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmN=
lPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzA2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB3afe7f05" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked about the=C2=A0Crypto Capital=
 aftermath in 2019</a>; this approach=C2=A0did not=C2=A0<em>avoid=C2=A0</em=
>regulatory trouble for Tether.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are other, more theoretically interestin=
g approaches. One good one is to do everything, as it were, synthetically. =
Your problems are=C2=A0with getting dollars, hanging onto the dollars, and =
wiring back dollars.=C2=A0<em>Issuing Tethers=C2=A0</em>on the blockchain i=
s the easy part of your business. If you can issue Tethers=C2=A0<em>without=
=C2=A0</em>getting dollars, that would simplify things. Of course then you =
wouldn=E2=80=99t have dollars! The whole point of Tether is to be backed by=
 dollars, to occasionally release auditor-flavored reports that loosely sug=
gest that Tether is fully backed by dollars.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you could imagine a system that is like:</=
p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some crypto exchange or trading firm h=
as an easier time getting dollars than you do.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">So they get dollars and turn them into some sort of crypto-nat=
ive form of value. Another stablecoin, maybe.=C2=A0Or just Bitcoin, really.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They give you the crypto-native f=
orm of value in exchange for Tether.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">You never have to touch dollars, avoiding a lot of headaches for you.</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They do the cash-out too.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Someone else =E2=80=94=C2=A0some independent t=
hird party with its own banking relationships =E2=80=94=C2=A0is handling th=
e dollars, so you don=E2=80=99t have to. And in fact Tether seems to deal m=
ainly with large customers =E2=80=94=C2=A0crypto exchanges and big traders =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0rather than letting every retail investor buy and sell USDT =
with Tether directly, which does make life easier: Tether=E2=80=99s banking=
 life is simpler if it has a few big customers making occasional trades tha=
n if it is sending and receiving money with hundreds of counterparties a da=
y. But it would be even simpler if it did mostly non-cash trading even with=
 them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t think that is a huge part of T=
ether=E2=80=99s business, but <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/30747147.267413/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9yaXNpbmc=
tdGV0aGVyLWxvYW5zLWFkZC1yaXNrLXRvLXN0YWJsZWNvaW4tY3J5cHRvLXdvcmxkLTExNjY5OD=
c1NTkwP21vZD1ocF9sZWFkX3BvczQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7b4b87ed" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
here is another Journal story from December</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company behind the tether stablecoin has i=
ncreasingly been lending its own coins to customers rather than selling the=
m for hard currency upfront. The shift adds to risks that the company may n=
ot have enough liquid assets to pay redemptions in a crisis.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tether Holdings Ltd. says it lends only to eli=
gible customers and requires that borrowers post lots of =E2=80=9Cextremely=
 liquid=E2=80=9D collateral, which could be sold for dollars if borrowers d=
efault.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These loans have appeared for several quarters=
 in the financial reports that Tether shows on its website. In the most rec=
ent report, they reached $6.1 billion as of Sept. 30, or 9% of the company=
=E2=80=99s total assets. They were $4.1 billion, or 5% of total assets, at =
the end of 2021.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tether calls them =E2=80=9Csecured loans=E2=80=
=9D and discloses little about the borrowers or the collateral accepted. Al=
ex Welch, a Tether spokeswoman, confirmed that all of the secured loans lis=
ted in the reports were issued and denominated in tether. The company said =
the loans were short-term and that Tether holds the collateral.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you sell USDT for dollars, you have to do a=
 dollar transfer; if you lend USDT secured by Bitcoin, you don=E2=80=99t. W=
e <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30747147.267413/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMDEvc2J=
mLW1pc3NlZC1mdHgtcy1yaXNrcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzA2MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaX=
VtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMDYmdXRtX2NhbXBha=
WduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6830138c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked about=
 that=C2=A0story at the time</a>, and I wrote, somewhat exasperatedly:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The thing with Tether is that ther=
e=E2=80=99s like $65 billion outstanding, it pays no interest and one-month=
 US Treasury bills yield like 3.8%. People do not give Tether money in orde=
r to earn interest on it; they give Tether money in order to get back USDT =
to use for crypto transactions. If you were Tether, you could just park the=
ir money in the safest and most liquid possible investments and earn billio=
ns of dollars of revenue that you get to keep. This is a very good and easy=
 business. You don=E2=80=99t need to do anything else. When people call you=
 up for loans, instead of evaluating their collateral and creditworthiness =
and negotiating good documentation and having a prudent risk management and=
 monitoring system, you could just say =E2=80=9Cno we=E2=80=99re good=E2=80=
=9D and buy Treasuries and sleep well on your giant pile of money.</p></blo=
ckquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But of course I was wrong:=C2=A0<em>In princip=
le=C2=A0</em>Tether has a very good and easy business, but=C2=A0<em>in prac=
tice=C2=A0</em>it is weirdly difficult, and issuing USDT in exchange for Bi=
tcoin collateral might in fact be easier and safer than issuing USDT in exc=
hange for dollars in the bank. To get dollars in the bank, you need a bank.=
</p>
